---
import Layout from "../layouts/layout.astro";

const railItems = [
  ["Registry", "NCC-83639"],
  ["Class", "Sagan-class Explorer"],
  ["Launched", "2403"],
  ["Assignment", "Frontier Initiative"],
  ["Archive Status", "Active"],
];
---

<Layout
  title="About the Project"
  description="Learn about USS Kepler, an independent Star Trek fan archive exploring service, citizenship, belonging, and civic institutions."
>
  <main class="interior-shell">
    <section class="page-hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">Project Overview</p>
      <h1>About the Project</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        USS Kepler is an independent Star Trek fan project exploring service,
        citizenship, belonging, and the institutions that connect worlds.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="content-layout">
      <article class="main-content">
        <section class="prose-block">
          <h2>What Is USS Kepler?</h2>
          <p>
            USS Kepler is a fictional Memory Alpha style archive documenting
            the operations of a Sagan-class starship during the early 25th
            century. Presented as a living historical repository, the project
            combines doctrine papers, mission records, personnel files,
            captain's logs, and archival analysis into a single narrative
            record.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose-block">
          <h2>Why This Project Exists</h2>
          <p>
            USS Kepler began with a problem. For years, Amid the Noise served as
            a home for essays about systems, institutions, technology, recovery,
            public life, and the ways people experience the structures around
            them. Over time, however, some of the questions that interested me
            most became difficult to explore through essays alone.
          </p>
          <p>
            What does belonging look like at an interstellar scale? How does a
            society remain connected across hundreds of worlds? What happens
            after a civilization solves many of the problems that dominate
            contemporary life?
          </p>
          <p>
            Those questions were not asking for another essay. They were asking
            for a setting.
          </p>
          <p>
            USS Kepler became that setting. Rather than building a traditional
            fan fiction project, I wanted to create something that felt like an
            archive: a place where mission reports, doctrine papers, personnel
            files, captain's logs, and historical records could accumulate into
            a larger picture of how a future Federation might actually function.
          </p>
          <p>
            If Amid the Noise asks what our institutions are, USS Kepler asks
            what they might become.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose-block">
          <h2>Relationship to Amid the Noise</h2>
          <p>
            USS Kepler is a companion project to Amid the Noise. While Amid the
            Noise focuses on essays, research, memoir, and civic observation,
            USS Kepler explores many of the same themes through speculative
            worldbuilding set within the Star Trek universe.
          </p>
          <p>
            The two projects share many of the same questions. Amid the Noise
            examines the present. USS Kepler explores what those same ideas
            might look like in a future that has survived long enough to become
            something more.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose-block section-note">
          <h2>Core Premise</h2>
          <p>
            The frontier is not only a place beyond the map. It is wherever
            distance begins to erode participation, trust, or belonging.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>

      <aside class="context-rail">
        <section class="rail-card metadata-card">
          <h2>Project Summary</h2>
          <dl>
            {railItems.map(([term, detail]) => (
              <div>
                <dt>{term}</dt>
                <dd>{detail}</dd>
              </div>
            ))}
          </dl>
        </section>
        <section class="rail-card related-card">
          <h2>Related Records</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="/mission">Mission</a></li>
            <li><a href="/ship">USS Kepler</a></li>
            <li><a href="/crew">Crew</a></li>
            <li><a href="/archive">Archive</a></li>
            <li><a href="/disclaimer">Disclaimer</a></li>
          </ul>
        </section>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
